title: For Sale:  1927 Izhevsk M91\30 Mosin Nagant on 1901 Imperial russian receiver.
postcontent:
For sale is my 1927 Izhevsk Mosin Nagant M91\30. This rifle is an ex-dragoon that was updated post 1930 to m91\30 specifications. As you can see in the pictures, the receiver has both the Imperial Russian eagle as well as the Soviet crest stamped on it. That's because the receiver is from a 1901 Izhevsk rifle. The Russians were very good at reusing good parts, so put the receiver back into service with a later produced barrel. The rifle is sitting in a good condition pre-war stock, with the screwed in escutcheons. 

The rifle also has the re-arsenal stamp /1\ (Triangle 1) which was formerly thought to have been an East German (DDR) marking. It has since been identified as referring to the facilities at 1861st ABV Moscow Military District - Liski.

Sales only to Washington residents, must show drivers license and sign a bill of sale stating your legally allowed to purchase and own a firearm.

title: For Sale:  T/C Omega z5
postcontent:
Omega Z5 50cal. w/ the weathershield coating on the barrel. DedNutz scope mount with Nikon Prostaff 2-7/32. Comes with 100 Hornady FTX 44 cal bullets, 50 Harvester 44/50cal sabots (correctly upsizes to 50cal), 60 CCI primers, 30 Hodgdon 777 pellets, and 9 T/C bullets w/ sabots that it didn't like at 100gr charge, but good enough to get you on paper. Bore was neglected when I got it, it mostly cleaned up after a good brushing. I don't have the means to remove the stock and soak it in solvent. Groups just fine with the FTX bullets.

The 44cal bullets come from the reloading section of Cabela's, and are much cheaper per hundred than a "muzzleloading bullet" I believe they were $40/100, whereas Powerbelts (and Hornady XTPs) from the muzzleloader section are $30/20. Greatly reduced costs, and generally better performance because you are tailoring your bullet weight to where you want it to match powder charge and twist rate in the barrel. I use the same setup in my Encore and it is deadly to 250 on deer, 300 on paper.
